'''Sorina Bucuraș''', better known as '''Sorina-Luminița Plăcintă''' (born '''Sorina Ștefan'''; February 6, 1965), is a [[Romania]]n engineer and politician. A member of the [[National Liberal Party (Romania)|National Liberal Party]] and formerly of the [[Democratic Liberal Party (Romania)|Democratic Liberal Party]] (PD-L), she was a member of the [[Senate of Romania|Romanian Senate]] for [[Vrancea County]] from 2008 to 2012. In the [[Emil Boc]] cabinet, she was [[Ministry of Youth and Sport (Romania)|Minister of Youth and Sport]] from July to December 2009, and interim [[Ministry of Relations with the Parliament (Romania)|Minister-Delegate for Relations with Parliament]] from October to December 2009.
==Biography==
She was born in [[Focșani]] and graduated from the Textile Technology and Chemistry faculty of the [[Gheorghe Asachi Technical University of Iași]] in 1989. From that year until 1993, she worked as an engineer at a [[worsted]] wool spinning mill in Focșani. From 1993 to 1994, she was assistant manager of an import-export firm in [[Bucharest]]. She was then active at three textile firms in Focșani until November 2008: at Soreste, she was stockholder, administrator and board president from 1994; at Milcofil, later purchased by Soreste, she was board president from 1997; and at Artifex, a joint venture between Soreste and [[Akris]], she was administrator and general director from 2005.<ref name="cvministru"/>{{dead link|date=April 2013}}
In 1997, Plăcintă joined the Democratic Party (PD; later evolved into the PD-L). At the [[Romanian legislative election, 2008|2008 election]], she won a Senate seat, and became vice president of that chamber's agriculture, forestry and rural development committee.<ref name="cvministru"/><ref>{{ro icon}} [http://www.alegeri.tv/alegeri-parlamentare-uninominale-2008/focsani/278/colegiul-uninominal-1 Election results], alegeri.tv; accessed July 15, 2009</ref> In July 2009, following the resignation of scandal-plagued minister [[Monica Iacob Ridzi]], Plăcintă was given the Youth and Sport portfolio and sworn in the same day.<ref>{{ro icon}} [http://www.mediafax.ro/sport/sorina-placinta-a-depus-juramantul-in-calitate-de-ministru-al-tineretului-si-sportului-video.html?1689;4639662 "Sorina Plăcintă a depus jurământul în calitate de ministru al Tineretului și Sportului" ("Sorina Plăcintă Takes Oath as Youth and Sport Minister")], Mediafax, 15 July 2009; accessed July 15, 2009</ref> Her appointment was criticised by [[Vrancea County]] Council and [[Social Democratic Party (Romania)|PSD]] chapter president [[Marian Oprișan]], who noted her links to the ministry were as close as those between "an old woman and a machine gun",<ref>{{ro icon}} [http://www.mediafax.ro/politic/oprisan-placinta-are-legatura-cu-tineretul-si-sportul-cum-are-baba-cu-mitraliera.html?1687;4639859 "Oprișan: Plăcintă are legătură cu tineretul și sportul cum are 'baba cu mitraliera'" ("Oprișan: Plăcintă's Links to Youth and Sport Are as Those of 'an Old Woman and a Machine Gun'")], Mediafax, 14 July 2009; accessed July 15, 2009</ref> and who pointed out she had contributed hundreds of thousands of [[euro]]s to her party.<ref>{{ro icon}} [http://www.mediafax.ro/sport/sorina-placinta-a-depus-juramantul-in-calitate-de-ministru-al-tineretului-si-sportului-video.html?1689;4639662 "Şeful judeţului Vrancea: Plăcintă nici măcar nu și-a câștigat mandatul" ("Vrancea County Chief: Plăcintă Did Not Even Win Her Office")], ''Ziarul Financiar'', 14 July 2009; accessed July 15, 2009</ref> The following month, she announced plans to cut in half the number of positions at her ministry.<ref>{{ro icon}} [http://www.romanialibera.ro/a162215/sorina-placinta-injumatateste-organigrama-mts.html "Sorina Plăcintă injumătățește organigrama MTS" ("Sorina Plăcintă Cuts in Half Ministry's Organisational Chart")], ''România liberă'', 12 August 2009; accessed September 7, 2009</ref> In October 2009, she became interim Minister for Relations with Parliament following the resignation of her PSD cabinet colleagues, including [[Victor Ponta]], the previous occupant of that ministry, holding the portfolio until December.<ref>{{ro icon}} Florina Zainescu, Lacrima Andreica and Adriana Duțulescu, [http://www.jurnalul.ro/stire-politic/guvernul-ingropat-cu-lautari-522702.html "Guvernul, îngropat cu lăutari" ("The Government, Interred with ''Lăutari''"], ''Jurnalul Național'', 2 October 2009; accessed July 23, 2010</ref><ref>{{ro icon}} [http://documentare.rompres.ro/guverne.php?i=120 Emil Boc II-III Government]; accessed September 4, 2010</ref> Her ministerial term ended when she was not reappointed to a new cabinet under Boc at the end of 2009.<ref>{{ro icon}} Monica Iordache Apostol, [http://www.jurnalul.ro/stire-special/guvernul-boc-zero-barat-553259.html "Guvernul Boc, zero barat" ("Boc Government, Total Zero")], ''Jurnalul Național'', 31 August 2010; accessed September 4, 2010</ref> Nearly a year later, she was elected a vice president of the Bucharest PD-L chapter.<ref>{{ro icon}} Cristina Iana, Alina Vasile, Valentina Deleanu, [http://www.adevarul.ro/actualitate/politica/PDL_Bucuresti_isi_alege_presedintele_0_376162499.html "Elena Udrea a fost aleasă preşedinte al PDL București: 'Eu vreau să scăpăm Bucureștiul de Sorin Oprescu'" ("Elena Udrea Elected President of Bucharest PDL: 'I Want Us to Get Bucharest Rid of Sorin Oprescu'"], ''Adevărul'', 21 November 2010; accessed November 21, 2010</ref> She resigned from the PD-L in June 2012, crossing to the PNL.<ref>{{ro icon}} Ioana Oancea, [http://www.adevarul.ro/actualitate/politica/Senatorul_Sorina_Placinta_a_demisionat_din_PDL_si_se_inscrie_in_PNL_0_718128298.html "Senatorul Sorina Plăcintă a demisionat din PDL și se înscrie în PNL" ("Senator Sorina Plăcintă Resigns from PDL and Joins PNL"], ''Adevărul'', 13 June 2012; accessed June 13, 2012</ref> She left the Senate at the end of 2012, having declined to run in [[Romanian legislative election, 2012|that year's election]].<ref>{{ro icon}} Andreea Udrea, [http://www.evz.ro/detalii/stiri/Sorina-Plcint-nu-mai-candideaz-pentru-Parlament-1001535.html "Sorina Plăcintă nu mai candidează pentru Parlament" ("Sorina Plăcintă No Longer Running for Parliament"], ''Evenimentul Zilei'', 19 September 2012; accessed April 24, 2013</ref>
She has one son from her first marriage, Andrei Plăcintă, who at one time lived in [[Montreux]], [[Switzerland]] and was pastor of the First Church of Atheism, an organisation seeking to eliminate religious belief from the world. Plăcintă herself is the ''[[ktitor]]issa'' of two [[Romanian Orthodox Church|Romanian Orthodox]] churches. In 2012, her son was sentenced to six years' imprisonment for attempted manslaughter, theft and indecent exposure, charges that stemmed from an incident that took place in Bucharest two years earlier;<ref>{{ro icon}} [http://www.ziua.net/news.php?data=2009-07-15&id=33311 "Boc o cocea deja: Ministrul Plăcintă o înlocuiește pe Ridzi. De la Comisia de agricultură şi cea de Afaceri externe, la Sport" ("Boc Was Already Preparing Her: Minister Plăcintă Is Replacing Ridzi. From the Agriculture and Foreign Affairs Committees, to Sport")]{{dead link|date=May 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}, ''Ziua'', 14 July 2009; accessed July 16, 2009</ref><ref>{{ro icon}} [http://www.ziua.net/display.php?data=2009-07-15&id=255774 "Cum acoperă PDL scandalul Iacob Ridzi" ("How the PDL Is Covering Up the Iacob Ridzi Scandal'")]{{dead link|date=May 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}, ''Ziua'', 15 July 2009; accessed July 16, 2009</ref><ref>{{ro icon}} Cornelia Drăghici, [http://www.gardianul.ro/Marti,-Sorina-Placinta-se-pregatea-sa-sarbatoreasca-Ziua-Transmisionistilor!-s138973.html "Marți, Sorina Plăcintă se pregătea să sărbătorească Ziua Transmisioniștilor!" ("On Tuesday, Sorina Plăcintă Was Preparing to Celebrate Transmission Engineers' Day!")], ''Gardianul'', 16 July 2009; accessed September 6, 2009</ref><ref>{{ro icon}} [http://www.adevarul.ro/actualitate/eveniment/Andrei_Placinta-fiul_senatorului_Sorina_Placinta-a_fost_condamnat_la_sase_ani_de_inchisoare_cu_executare_0_731927134.html "Andrei Plăcintă, fiul senatorului Sorina Plăcintă, condamnat la 6 ani de închisoare cu executare" ("Andrei Plăcintă, Son of Senator Sorina Plăcintă, Sentenced to 6 Years' Imprisonment")], ''Adevărul'', 6 July 2012; accessed July 23, 2012</ref> the sentence was ultimately reduced to four and a half years.<ref>{{ro icon}} Mihai Stoica, [http://adevarul.ro/news/eveniment/andrei-placinta-magistrati-1_52778a01c7b855ff56b6871b/index.html "Andrei Plăcintă, fiul fostei senatoare Sorina Plăcintă, va sta patru ani și șase luni după gratii" ("Andrei Plăcintă, Son of Former Senator Sorina Plăcintă, Will Spend Four Years and Six Months behind Bars")], ''Adevărul'', 4 November 2013; accessed November 6, 2013</ref> Her second husband was Stefan Sobota, her former business partner, who immigrated from [[Sweden]] in 1992;<ref name="cvministru">{{ro icon}} [http://www.mts.gov.ro/ministru.php Profile at the Ministry of Youth and Sport site]; accessed July 15, 2009</ref><ref>{{ro icon}} [http://www.dialogtextil.ro/arh/2002/iul_aug_2002/interviu.htm "Oameni deosebiți în locuri deosebite" ("Special People in Special Places")], ''Dialog Textil'', July 2002; accessed July 15, 2009 {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060928105958/http://www.dialogtextil.ro/arh/2002/iul_aug_2002/interviu.htm |date=September 28, 2006 }}</ref> in 2010, she announced they would divorce.<ref>{{ro icon}} Iulia Creţu, [http://www.ziaruldevrancea.ro/index.php?articol=40953 "Sorina Plăcintă a confirmat divorţul de Stefan Sobota" ("Sorina Plăcintă Confirms Divorce from Stefan Sobota'")], ''Ziarul de Vrancea'', 21 January 2010; accessed September 4, 2010</ref> This had taken place by the following year, when she secretly married urologist Viorel Bucuraș, adopting his surname in 2012.<ref>{{ro icon}} Ștefan Borcea, [http://www.adevarul.ro/locale/focsani/Senatorul_de_Vrancea_Sorina_Placinta_s-a_casatorit_in_secret_0_551345062.html "Senatorul de Vrancea Sorina Plăcintă s-a căsătorit în secret" ("Vrancea Senator Sorina Plăcintă Secretly Marries")], ''Adevărul'', 9 September 2011; accessed July 23, 2012</ref><ref>{{ro icon}} Ștefan Borcea, [http://www.adevarul.ro/locale/focsani/Senatorul_PNL_Sorina_Placinta_si-a_schimbat_numele_0_742125847.html "Senatorul PNL Sorina Plăcintă și-a schimbat numele" ("PNL Senator Sorina Plăcintă Changes Name")], ''Adevărul'', 23 July 2012; accessed July 23, 2012</ref>
